# Human Writing Style

Write like a developer explaining things to another developer on the team. Avoid patterns that read as AI-generated boilerplate.

## Do not use

- Em dashes or en dashes. Use a hyphen with spaces, or split into two sentences.
- Section symbols (the legal section sign). Write "Section" or rephrase.
- Decorative emoji or icon markers in docs, rules, templates, or ADRs.
- Unicode bullets or status dots in prose or tables. Use `-`, `*`, or plain words (Yes / No / Optional).
- Fancy Unicode arrows in prose. Use `->`, `<-`, `=>`, or words ("then", "leads to").
- Curly/smart quotes. Use straight quotes.
- The single-character ellipsis. Use three periods.

## Prefer

- Short, direct sentences.
- Plain markdown: headers, bullets, tables without ornament.
- Technical terms when accurate; plain language when teaching.
- ASCII in diagrams when needed.

## Code comment examples

```typescript
// BAD: business logic in the route handler
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const body = await req.json();
  await prisma.order.create({ data: body });
}

// GOOD: parse input, call service
export async function POST(req: Request) {
  const input = createOrderSchema.parse(await req.json());
  return NextResponse.json(await orderService.create(input));
}
```

## Applies to

All files under `docs/`, `templates/`, `AGENTS.md`, `README.md`, `.cursor/rules/`, `.cursor/skills/`, and `.cursor/agents/` unless a legal template explicitly requires formal statutory wording from a lawyer.
